{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3dc07a5b-313d-4eb2-b447-39ed6d2a814b","content":"Here's what breaks in each case and the fixes:\n\n---\n\n### 1. `SpanHelper.cs` — Stricter ref-safety escape analysis\n\nC# 15 tightens span escape rules. `[x * 2]` targeting `Span<int>` is implicitly stack-allocated and scoped to the loop body. Assigning it to `results` (which lives in the outer scope) is now a ref-safety error — the stack memory becomes invalid after each iteration.\n\n**Fix** — use a `List<int>` instead of span reassignment:\n\n```csharp\npublic static int[] ProcessItems(int[] source)\n{\n    var results = new List<int>();\n    foreach (var x in source)\n        results.Add(x * 2);\n    return results.ToArray();\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n### 2. `Metadata.cs` — `this` disallowed in `nameof` within attributes\n\nC# 15 no longer permits `this` inside `nameof` in attribute arguments. Attributes are compile-time metadata — `this` is an instance expression that doesn't exist in that context. (Previously the compiler allowed it since `nameof` never evaluates its operand.)\n\n**Fix** — drop the `this` qualifier:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Obsolete(nameof(Endpoint))]\nvoid LegacyConnect() { }\n```\n\n---\n\n### 3. `Pipeline.cs` — `with` is now a keyword inside collection expressions\n\nC# 15 expands `with` as a keyword in collection expression contexts. Inside `[...]`, the parser interprets `with(x, y)` as keyword syntax rather than a method call, causing a parse error.\n\n**Fix** — escape with `@`:\n\n```csharp\nobject @with(object a, object b) => (a, b);\nobject[] items = [@with(x, y), z];\n```\n\nOr better, rename the method to avoid the keyword collision entirely (e.g., `Combine`).","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"b9174d62-d984-450f-9f11-03a16302e0d1","outputTokens":470,"requestId":"680B:1E3875:272E0FE:2B1FC3E:69FD29D3"},"id":"a912c5c9-2188-421e-ac4a-576394b0fad8","timestamp":"2026-05-08T00:10:06.051Z","parentId":"51626e9c-4bea-413d-b876-9b353bbb7b38"}
